WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.400
Okay, so I want to talk to you today about the Shiny Server Pro architecture, and give

00:00:15.400 --> 00:00:21.160
you a bit of a feel for how things are organized and how things are run within Shiny Server

00:00:21.160 --> 00:00:22.559
and Shiny Server Pro.

00:00:22.559 --> 00:00:28.520
All right, so first of all, Shiny Server Pro is kind of an, can be viewed as an extension

00:00:28.520 --> 00:00:36.320
of the open source Shiny Server package, which we generally just call Shiny Server.

00:00:36.320 --> 00:00:41.380
And so basically, you can view Pro as kind of enhancements and new sets of features that

00:00:41.380 --> 00:00:43.520
add on to the open source package.

00:00:43.520 --> 00:00:49.360
So when you talk about the architecture of Pro or open source, it probably makes sense

00:00:49.360 --> 00:00:55.119
to start with a discussion about the open source Shiny Server, and then we can kind

00:00:55.119 --> 00:00:58.840
of grow from there into what Pro adds on to that.

00:00:58.840 --> 00:01:04.000
But, you know, I mentioned here a couple of the features that are often most compelling

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:05.000
for Pro.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:10.080
So, you know, we do user authentication with whether that's LDAP or Active Directory, and

00:01:10.080 --> 00:01:14.760
then also we do application scaling across multiple processes for a single application,

00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:17.760
which is helpful.

00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:23.639
So okay, so to go kind of all the way down the hole, we get down into the Shiny package,

00:01:23.639 --> 00:01:30.000
and I suspect that most of you are familiar with Shiny, but basically Shiny is, as you

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:35.800
know, an R package, but what's important to realize is that Shiny speaks WebSocket.

00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:40.160
And so what that means is that any browser that's compatible with WebSocket can connect

00:01:40.160 --> 00:01:46.000
directly to a Shiny process and do, you know, the communications there back and forth between

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:47.800
those two entities.

00:01:47.800 --> 00:01:52.199
So that's great, and you probably notice this when you're developing applications locally.

00:01:52.199 --> 00:01:54.839
So if you're using RStudio, for instance, and you press run app, you're going to get

00:01:54.839 --> 00:01:55.839
a little viewer.

00:01:55.839 --> 00:01:59.839
That viewer is communicating directly to your R process, or, you know, if you open in a

00:01:59.839 --> 00:02:03.720
browser, you're communicating directly with an R process, and there's no Shiny server

00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:08.240
intermediary between those two, and that's because Shiny speaks WebSockets.

00:02:08.240 --> 00:02:15.160
So it is possible to open a direct connection from a browser into the Shiny process.

00:02:15.160 --> 00:02:17.399
So that's great, but there are a couple of limitations on this.

00:02:17.399 --> 00:02:22.919
First of all, as I mentioned, that only works for browsers that can communicate over WebSockets,

00:02:22.919 --> 00:02:28.240
and so that rules out Internet Explorer 8 and 9 and some other versions of Firefox and

00:02:28.240 --> 00:02:30.600
Chrome and things like that.

00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:34.279
The other problem is that the Shiny process has to be running at the moment you try to

00:02:34.279 --> 00:02:39.000
open a connection to it, and so that can be a little complicated in that if you have,

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.639
you know, as an organization, maybe you have, you know, hundreds of Shiny applications that

00:02:42.639 --> 00:02:46.600
you've developed, and at any given time, maybe, you know, a handful of them are actually

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:49.720
being used and interacted with.

00:02:49.720 --> 00:02:53.679
The problem is here that, you know, in order to communicate, Shiny would have to be running

00:02:53.679 --> 00:02:57.679
all of, like, you would have to be running one process for each of those applications

00:02:57.679 --> 00:03:02.279
all the time around the clock, and that creates a lot of problems in terms of resource utilization.

00:03:02.279 --> 00:03:07.559
If you're trying to run these, you know, hundreds or even thousands of processes all the time,

00:03:07.559 --> 00:03:12.600
even though many of them may not be used, you know, but, you know, a few minutes a day.

00:03:12.600 --> 00:03:18.199
So there are a couple of limitations to just running Shiny on the bare metal, but it is possible.

00:03:18.199 --> 00:03:23.479
So Shiny server sets out to accomplish a few goals.

00:03:23.479 --> 00:03:28.000
The couple that are interesting for this discussion are, first of all, it should start and stop

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:35.240
Shiny processes on demand and as needed, and also it should translate non-WebSocket traffic

00:03:35.240 --> 00:03:38.919
into WebSocket traffic that Shiny can understand.

00:03:38.919 --> 00:03:43.119
And then finally, it can also map different URLs to particular applications.

00:03:43.119 --> 00:03:48.240
So if you were just to run an army of Shiny processes on your bare machine, all of those

00:03:48.240 --> 00:03:51.520
would have to run on different ports, and so your users would need to enter a port number

00:03:51.520 --> 00:03:55.039
in order to get to an application, and it would be, you know, a little sloppy.

00:03:55.039 --> 00:04:01.000
And so Shiny server offers a kind of a cleaner, more convenient way to be able to navigate

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:04.800
between the different applications, and we do that by offering a few different hosting

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:05.800
modes.

00:04:05.800 --> 00:04:06.800
So you could just host one application.

00:04:06.800 --> 00:04:11.679
You could allow users to host their own applications, or you could host an entire directory of applications,

00:04:11.679 --> 00:04:13.759
and you can do these at different URL subspaces.

00:04:13.759 --> 00:04:22.600
So it just allows you to kind of more meaningfully manage, you know, many Shiny applications.

00:04:22.600 --> 00:04:24.880
And so a couple of these to kind of revisit.

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:29.640
So starting and stopping Shiny processes, so again, this is, you know, if you're running

00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:33.119
this naively, you would need to be running that Shiny process all the time, but because

00:04:33.119 --> 00:04:37.799
you're running Shiny server as kind of this long-running, you know, always-on daemon,

00:04:37.799 --> 00:04:42.399
what that means is that when a user goes to connect into the Shiny process, if it's not

00:04:42.399 --> 00:04:48.000
running now, Shiny server can kind of hold that request for a second while it goes to

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.600
start the Shiny process, and then once the Shiny process is ready, it can let the traffic

00:04:52.600 --> 00:04:57.720
through into that process, so it can kind of broker and manage the communications between

00:04:57.720 --> 00:05:01.399
applications that may or may not be running at the moment they're requested.

00:05:01.399 --> 00:05:05.239
And then also if it notices that all the users have left and that application's been

00:05:05.239 --> 00:05:09.399
idle for some configurable length of time, then it can go ahead and reap those processes

00:05:09.399 --> 00:05:13.160
to free up some more resources for other applications.

00:05:13.160 --> 00:05:15.920
And again, like I mentioned, older versions of Internet Explorer are not going to be able

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:22.160
to handle WebSockets natively, and so Shiny server uses a library called sock.js, which

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:26.399
basically allows you to work as if you were working with WebSockets, but it will kind

00:05:26.399 --> 00:05:30.519
of gracefully fall back into other protocols as needed.

00:05:30.519 --> 00:05:34.679
And that's actually really important, even if you're not planning to support older versions

00:05:34.679 --> 00:05:40.119
of Internet Explorer, because many networks, if you're using older network equipment that

00:05:40.119 --> 00:05:46.519
was designed before WebSockets gained popularity, then you'll actually end up in a situation

00:05:46.519 --> 00:05:50.880
where they may be dropping or blocking WebSocket traffic, and we see this quite a bit, especially

00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:56.000
at universities and academic settings, they for some reason tend to have network equipment

00:05:56.000 --> 00:06:02.040
that isn't friendly with WebSockets, so you can kind of end up in the situation where

00:06:02.040 --> 00:06:05.559
even if you're using all the latest and greatest technology, there may be some router between

00:06:05.559 --> 00:06:11.200
you and your client that is going to interrupt your WebSocket traffic, and so it's nice to

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:16.320
have a technology that will allow you to fall back to something that is supported if needed,

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:20.040
so that ends up being a pretty important feature.

00:06:20.040 --> 00:06:25.920
And then as we already discussed, being able to map URLs to different applications.

00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:30.200
So kind of an overview of the architecture, you can envision it looking something like

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:31.200
this.

00:06:31.200 --> 00:06:37.399
So you have a variety of users over here, I don't know if you can see, you have your

00:06:37.399 --> 00:06:43.559
variety of users over here, which could be a handful, or we run servers where there are

00:06:43.559 --> 00:06:47.959
hundreds of concurrent connections from different users around the world, but they're all opening

00:06:47.959 --> 00:06:53.640
connections into your Shiny server instance, which again is kind of this always-on server

00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:57.920
process that's running as a daemon on your server.

00:06:57.920 --> 00:07:03.959
And then it's going to open and close, or start and stop these Shiny applications, and

00:07:03.959 --> 00:07:10.239
kind of proxy the traffic as it goes through from users' browsers into the Shiny applications,

00:07:10.239 --> 00:07:13.559
and so what this typically looks like, just to give you a feel if you're going to get

00:07:13.559 --> 00:07:18.119
down to the network level, the first request, of course, is just for kind of the root URL

00:07:18.119 --> 00:07:22.440
of some application, Shiny server would go in and inspect, is that application already

00:07:22.440 --> 00:07:23.440
online?

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:30.880
So let's say it maps some URL to app one, so it would go through and say, is app one

00:07:30.880 --> 00:07:31.880
already online?

00:07:31.880 --> 00:07:35.440
If it is, it'll proxy the traffic through, if it's not, it'll start app one, and then

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:38.920
proxy the traffic through.

00:07:38.920 --> 00:07:44.079
And then just kind of continue to keep these channels open between the user and the application.

00:07:44.079 --> 00:07:48.320
So what this looks like at a network level, the first request is going to be for kind

00:07:49.320 --> 00:07:53.720
of the root URL of that application, and then that's going to return some HTML that is going

00:07:53.720 --> 00:07:58.079
to kind of point the browser to different static assets that may be of relevance to

00:07:58.079 --> 00:08:01.480
CSS files and JavaScript files and things like that.

00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:07.320
And so it'll open up more connections for all of those files, and then eventually it'll

00:08:07.320 --> 00:08:12.160
actually open a WebSocket or WebSocket-like connection that will be persistent between

00:08:12.160 --> 00:08:17.040
that browser and that Shiny application, and that's kind of how Shiny, the Shiny magic

00:08:17.040 --> 00:08:23.600
works is via that WebSocket or that WebSocket-like channel that allows the user and the Shiny

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:28.600
process to communicate back and forth for as long as that connection is open.

00:08:28.600 --> 00:08:36.080
So this is kind of hopefully gives you a feel for sort of the architecture of Shiny Server

00:08:36.080 --> 00:08:37.080
here.

00:08:37.080 --> 00:08:42.359
What's, well, yeah, so I'll get to that here in a little bit.

00:08:42.359 --> 00:08:47.599
So a couple of points here, just as I mentioned, the user's connection to the Shiny Server

00:08:47.599 --> 00:08:51.960
may or may not be a WebSocket, though these connections between Shiny Server and the Shiny

00:08:51.960 --> 00:08:57.719
process must be WebSocket connections, because that's the only protocol that Shiny can understand.

00:08:57.719 --> 00:09:00.599
But these external connections, again, may or may not be WebSockets, they don't have

00:09:00.599 --> 00:09:01.599
to be.

00:09:01.599 --> 00:09:05.559
If you're using an older browser or some network intermediary is blocking WebSockets, that's

00:09:05.559 --> 00:09:10.119
fine, we can handle other protocols as well.

00:09:10.119 --> 00:09:12.799
And then the other point here, of course, is that Shiny applications are going to be

00:09:12.799 --> 00:09:18.479
started and stopped as needed, and so the running processes may not encompass all of

00:09:18.479 --> 00:09:22.119
the available applications that we know about, you know, there may be others that we could

00:09:22.119 --> 00:09:25.359
start as a request comes in for that application.

00:09:25.359 --> 00:09:26.359
Okay.

00:09:26.359 --> 00:09:31.599
So that hopefully gives you a feel for Shiny Server, which is kind of a simplified architectural

00:09:31.599 --> 00:09:35.280
diagram compared to what you're going to encounter in Shiny Server Pro.

00:09:35.760 --> 00:09:40.599
So Shiny Server Pro adds a variety of different features, and of course we enumerate all these

00:09:40.599 --> 00:09:44.840
on the product pages on our website, but a couple that are of relevance today, if you're

00:09:44.840 --> 00:09:50.000
considering doing something like high availability or load balancing between Shiny Server processes,

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:54.280
there are a couple features that you need to be aware of in Shiny Server Pro.

00:09:54.280 --> 00:09:59.520
So again, the Pro product is going to add a few features like authentication and more

00:09:59.520 --> 00:10:05.679
scalability, so being able to support a single Shiny application having multiple processes.

00:10:05.679 --> 00:10:10.479
One of the nice benefits here, if you're looking at doing high availability or load balancing

00:10:10.479 --> 00:10:15.280
across multiple instances, is that there's really not a whole lot of centralized storage

00:10:15.280 --> 00:10:21.080
to coordinate between multiple Shiny Server Pro instances, so you don't necessarily need

00:10:21.080 --> 00:10:25.919
like an NFS share or, you know, some centralized database or something like that.

00:10:25.919 --> 00:10:32.080
Most of the state is actually kept on the user's browser, which I'll kind of explain

00:10:32.080 --> 00:10:37.880
here in a minute, but there's not a whole lot of centralized storage, so the only statefulness

00:10:37.880 --> 00:10:43.239
that you need to worry about is just the information that pertains to the open connections right

00:10:43.239 --> 00:10:49.280
now at that moment, and so you need to know about which user is mapped to which worker

00:10:49.280 --> 00:10:53.760
and how to be able to connect those two entities consistently, and I'll discuss that here in

00:10:53.760 --> 00:10:59.000
a diagram in a second, but, you know, as I mentioned, most of the information is actually

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:02.799
stored in the browser, so the authentication information in particular is actually stored

00:11:02.799 --> 00:11:06.719
in an encrypted cookie that gets placed on the user's browser, so you don't need to worry

00:11:06.719 --> 00:11:11.320
about a session store in, you know, Redis or a database or anything like that.

00:11:11.320 --> 00:11:17.919
That's all just kind of pushed out into the user's browser, which is nice, so you won't

00:11:17.919 --> 00:11:22.320
need to worry about coordinating any central storage like that.

00:11:22.640 --> 00:11:28.320
Okay, so this is a very similar diagram for ShinyServer Pro as we saw with ShinyServer,

00:11:28.320 --> 00:11:33.599
but there's one distinction, which is that you can see that a single application may

00:11:33.599 --> 00:11:37.320
be backed by multiple workers, and that's kind of what I was referencing earlier when

00:11:37.320 --> 00:11:40.159
I was saying that, you know, you can scale an application to multiple processes.

00:11:40.159 --> 00:11:49.400
That's one of the big selling points for Pro, so what that means is that you can have different

00:11:49.400 --> 00:11:55.119
workers each with different IDs backing a single application.

00:11:55.119 --> 00:12:01.760
It's important that you understand that distinction because when a user opens a connection to

00:12:01.760 --> 00:12:06.200
ShinyServer Pro, but ultimately into a Shiny process, it's very important that that user

00:12:06.200 --> 00:12:13.440
be consistently mapped back to that same Shiny process, and so there are some cases where

00:12:13.440 --> 00:12:18.280
that's really important in Shiny, but it's extremely important in R Markdown, and you'll

00:12:18.280 --> 00:12:23.960
notice if you're hosting any kind of R Markdown documents, you'll notice very quickly that

00:12:23.960 --> 00:12:28.080
things are going to start breaking in kind of weird ways if your users are not being

00:12:28.080 --> 00:12:33.719
deterministically mapped back to the worker that they open the connection on.

00:12:33.719 --> 00:12:40.080
So basically what that means is that if I as a user come in and request a page, if I

00:12:40.080 --> 00:12:44.239
request Apple One, then ShinyServer Pro is going to go through and see, do I have any

00:12:44.239 --> 00:12:46.200
workers associated with Apple One yet?

00:12:46.200 --> 00:12:51.280
Yes, I have two, and now it's going to pick one of these based on whichever one has the

00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:56.440
least load currently, and so let's say that's Worker 13, so it'll point me to Worker 13.

00:12:56.440 --> 00:13:01.919
Worker 13 will fulfill my original request for the base URL, but then what I'm saying

00:13:01.919 --> 00:13:06.159
is that every HTML request and ultimately the web socket that gets opened between the

00:13:06.159 --> 00:13:11.320
user and that application must always be routed to Worker 13.

00:13:11.320 --> 00:13:15.700
So we handle, in this architectural diagram that you can see here, we handle all this

00:13:15.700 --> 00:13:17.719
complexity for you in ShinyServer Pro.

00:13:17.719 --> 00:13:23.960
So we ensure that when a user opens a connection to a Shiny application, that all the traffic

00:13:23.960 --> 00:13:28.880
that they're going to have associated with that application will always be directed back

00:13:28.880 --> 00:13:33.719
to that individual Shiny application, or that Shiny process rather, and so that's important.

00:13:33.719 --> 00:13:38.159
So you'll never have a user that opens a connection where some traffic is served by Worker 13

00:13:38.159 --> 00:13:39.599
and some is served by Worker 27.

00:13:39.599 --> 00:13:43.119
That would never happen in this single instance of ShinyServer Pro scenario.

00:13:43.119 --> 00:13:46.200
You would always get the same worker.

00:13:46.200 --> 00:13:50.799
So we handle that complexity for you, but that's important to understand if you're thinking

00:13:50.799 --> 00:13:54.080
about load balancing, which I'll talk about here in a second.

00:13:54.080 --> 00:13:57.919
So I think this is just kind of making the point that I just made, that if you have a

00:13:57.919 --> 00:14:03.320
single channel between a user and a process, that always must be consistent.

00:14:03.320 --> 00:14:06.559
You always need that same channel to be open.

00:14:06.559 --> 00:14:09.080
Okay.

00:14:09.080 --> 00:14:13.419
So now if we're looking at doing load balancing or high availability of ShinyServer Pro instance,

00:14:13.419 --> 00:14:18.119
this is where you need to start thinking about the implications of some of those things.

00:14:18.119 --> 00:14:23.479
So first of all, if we put a load balancer here in front of two ShinyServer Pro instances,

00:14:23.479 --> 00:14:30.320
you'll notice that both ShinyServer Pro instances may be running processes associated with App1.

00:14:30.320 --> 00:14:33.880
So in this case, we have one ShinyServer Pro over here that's hosting two workers associated

00:14:33.880 --> 00:14:39.840
with App1 and one over here that's also hosting two workers of App1.

00:14:39.840 --> 00:14:43.719
And so this is nice because these could be running and typically would be running on

00:14:43.719 --> 00:14:48.280
different physical boxes and may have separate network connections and things like that.

00:14:48.280 --> 00:14:52.239
So this will allow you to do high availability and redundancy.

00:14:52.239 --> 00:14:57.739
But what's nice about this is that then any resources that you're using here, if you're

00:14:57.739 --> 00:15:01.539
doing real-time streaming, for instance, onto one of these Shiny processes, then you

00:15:01.539 --> 00:15:06.659
need to be able to kind of monitor, you know, frequent updates to data or you're storing

00:15:06.659 --> 00:15:09.900
a large amount of memory or something like that, then it can be really nice to be able

00:15:09.900 --> 00:15:16.419
to scale this out to multiple physical boxes, which you can do as in this diagram.

00:15:16.419 --> 00:15:18.820
But a couple of things that you'll need to be aware of in doing so.

00:15:18.820 --> 00:15:22.219
So first of all, you'll obviously need a load balancer in front of the two instances that's

00:15:22.219 --> 00:15:25.979
going to balance traffic between the two.

00:15:25.979 --> 00:15:32.780
And keep in mind that there are WebSocket-friendly load balancers, like NGINX, I believe, now

00:15:32.780 --> 00:15:37.659
can support WebSockets and load balance traffic just fine with those.

00:15:37.659 --> 00:15:42.700
And Amazon DLB, if you're on Amazon Web Services and things like that, they can do these well.

00:15:42.700 --> 00:15:48.940
But older proxies or load balancers may not do WebSockets completely, they may not support

00:15:48.940 --> 00:15:49.940
that protocol.

00:15:49.940 --> 00:15:53.780
And so just be aware that if you're using an older load balancer or one that doesn't

00:15:53.780 --> 00:16:00.419
support WebSockets, then all of the WebSocket-like connections coming in from users will be degraded

00:16:00.419 --> 00:16:03.500
down to some other protocol that is compatible.

00:16:03.500 --> 00:16:10.780
So it's not necessary that this be WebSocket-friendly, but just be aware that WebSockets are kind

00:16:10.780 --> 00:16:15.979
of going to be the most efficient and lowest latency channel between the Shiny process

00:16:15.979 --> 00:16:16.979
and the user.

00:16:16.979 --> 00:16:22.260
And so just be aware that if you have a non-WebSocket-compatible load balancer, that there's just going to

00:16:22.260 --> 00:16:25.219
be a little bit more latency and a little bit more network overhead between your users

00:16:25.219 --> 00:16:27.659
and your Shiny instances.

00:16:27.659 --> 00:16:34.059
Really it's probably going to be negligible, but just so you're informed.

00:16:34.059 --> 00:16:37.500
And then the point that I was making earlier is that there's no state that you need to

00:16:37.500 --> 00:16:39.580
worry about coordinating between these two instances.

00:16:39.580 --> 00:16:43.979
So you'll notice we don't have some NFS share mounted between these two or some database

00:16:43.979 --> 00:16:45.539
that's coordinating between these two.

00:16:45.539 --> 00:16:47.500
You don't need to worry about any of that.

00:16:47.500 --> 00:16:51.020
The one thing that you do need to be aware of, though, is that, again, as I emphasized

00:16:51.020 --> 00:16:56.780
earlier, a single user must be directed deterministically back to the same process.

00:16:56.780 --> 00:17:01.859
And so what that means, again, we handle the complexity within Shiny server, but you would

00:17:01.859 --> 00:17:07.060
then be responsible for handling the complexity of ensuring that a single user is always going

00:17:07.060 --> 00:17:10.020
to get load balanced to the same Shiny server instance.

00:17:10.020 --> 00:17:16.619
So this is, as you probably know, called sticky sessions or sticky load balancing.

00:17:16.619 --> 00:17:20.219
What that would mean, then, is that when a user comes into your load balancer, if they've

00:17:20.219 --> 00:17:23.660
already been directed to a single instance of the Shiny Server Pro instance for some

00:17:23.660 --> 00:17:28.979
application, that they would continue to have all of their traffic, either HTTP or WebSocket,

00:17:28.979 --> 00:17:32.140
directed back to that same instance, and then from there, we'll handle the rest of the complexity

00:17:32.140 --> 00:17:35.300
of making sure that they get back to the right worker.

00:17:35.300 --> 00:17:40.140
So you would need to be aware of that if you're getting into a high availability situation.

00:17:40.140 --> 00:17:42.900
The one other piece here, and this is kind of nuanced, we can talk about the details

00:17:42.900 --> 00:17:50.060
of this later, but so, again, since we're using encrypted cookies to store the user's

00:17:50.420 --> 00:17:56.300
authentication information on their browser, you would just need to be aware that the two

00:17:56.300 --> 00:18:01.660
Shiny Server Pro instances should probably use the same key when going to encrypt those

00:18:01.660 --> 00:18:06.540
cookies so that they can both understand the encrypted cookie that may be stored on the

00:18:06.540 --> 00:18:10.939
user's browser, regardless of where they get balanced in the future.

00:18:10.939 --> 00:18:16.339
So, again, we've done this before, and we've seen this model set up very well, where you

00:18:16.339 --> 00:18:20.380
do this high availability setup, just using sticky sessions, you'll just drop a cookie

00:18:20.380 --> 00:18:25.660
on the user's browser, either at that subdomain, or make it applicable to a certain path for

00:18:25.660 --> 00:18:30.619
the application, and then just make sure that for the rest of the session, any time that

00:18:30.619 --> 00:18:34.739
they go to access that application, that they're always deterministically back to the same

00:18:34.739 --> 00:18:35.739
Shiny Server Pro instance.

00:18:35.739 --> 00:18:37.939
And that is it.

00:18:46.339 --> 00:18:47.339
Thank you.

00:18:47.339 --> 00:18:48.339
And we'll see you next time.

00:18:48.339 --> 00:18:48.339


